13.4 Security Rules (Non-Negotiable)
These rules apply to every line of code in the project. Violations are blocking—code that breaks these rules must not be merged.
No hardcoded secrets. All API keys, JWT secrets, database URLs, and AWS credentials must come from environment variables via .env. Never commit .env files to version control.
AWS credentials stay server-side. AWS access keys, S3 bucket names, Textract configuration, and SQS queue URLs must never appear in frontend code, browser network requests, or client-side bundles. All AWS operations happen exclusively in the backend or Lambda handlers.
OpenAI API key stays server-side. The OpenAI SDK is a backend-only dependency. The key must never be referenced in frontend code, exposed in API responses, or logged.
JWT tokens are HttpOnly cookies. Access and refresh tokens are set as HttpOnly, Secure, SameSite=Strict cookies. Never store JWT tokens in localStorage or sessionStorage. Never expose tokens in API response bodies beyond the initial login response.
All queries scoped to authenticated user. Every database query that returns user-specific data must filter by the authenticated user’s ID or verify ownership. No IDOR vulnerabilities. Patron-role users must not access Admin or Staff endpoints.
RBAC enforced at the middleware level. Role checks (ADMIN, STAFF, PATRON) must happen in auth.middleware.ts via requireRole(), not in controllers or services. Never rely on frontend-only role checks.
No stack traces in production. All production errors return the universal error envelope (Section 7.1) with a generic message. Full stack traces are logged server-side via Morgan only.
S3 buckets are private. All book cover and spine images stored in S3 use private ACLs. Frontend access to images must go through pre-signed URLs generated by the backend. Never make S3 objects publicly readable.
File upload limits enforced. Multer is configured with a 10 MB limit. Reject files exceeding this size with HTTP 413. Only accept image MIME types (image/jpeg, image/png, image/webp) for the ingestion endpoint.
CORS origin is explicit. Never use wildcard (*) in production CORS configuration. The allowed origin must match FRONTEND_URL from the environment.
13.5 File Placement Rules
All source files must reside in the locations defined in Sections 9.5.1 and 9.5.2. Do not create files outside the established structure without amending this section. Key rules:
Frontend pages: One page.tsx per route segment under src/app/(dashboard)/. Default export required (Next.js convention).
Route-specific components: Co-located in src/app/(dashboard)/<feature>/components/. Named exports. Kebab-case filenames.
Shared components: Cross-route components go in src/components/<domain>/. PascalCase filenames. UI primitives in src/components/ui/ are shadcn-generated only—never hand-write them.
Backend layers: Routes define HTTP verbs and delegate to controllers. Controllers handle req/res and delegate to services. Services contain business logic and call Prisma. Never put business logic in controllers. Never import req/res objects in services.
Database access: All queries go through Prisma Client (src/lib/prisma.ts singleton). No raw SQL in application code. Migrations may use raw SQL.
