13.7 AI Ingestion Pipeline Rules
The AI ingestion pipeline (Section 8) has additional constraints due to its interaction with external services and its impact on catalog data integrity:
AI outputs are advisory only. No AI-generated metadata (Dewey classification, ISBN detection, title/author enrichment) may be written to the catalog automatically. All AI results must pass through the staff review interface before being committed.
Confidence scores are mandatory. Every AI response must include a confidence score between 0.0 and 1.0. The frontend must display this score to the reviewing staff member.
Current flow is synchronous. The current implementation uses POST /ingest/analyze (synchronous). The async architecture (SQS + Lambda) is planned but not yet wired. Do not implement the async endpoints (GET /ingest/jobs/:id, POST /ingest/jobs/:id/approve, POST /ingest/jobs/:id/reject) until the SQS integration is explicitly scheduled.
Textract errors are non-fatal. If AWS Textract fails or returns empty text, the ingestion response should still return with ocrText: null and allow the staff member to enter metadata manually. Never throw a 500 for an OCR failure.
Image cleanup. Uploaded images stored in Multer memory must not persist beyond the request lifecycle. Once uploaded to S3, the in-memory buffer must be released.
13.8 Library Map Rules
The 2D library map (React Flow) is a complex interactive component. Agents working on the map module must follow these constraints:
Map endpoints are not yet implemented. Section 7 notes that all /map/* routes currently return 501 Not Implemented. Do not build frontend map features that depend on backend persistence until the map API routes are implemented.
All map components live in src/components/map/. This is a shared component directory, not co-located under the /map route, because map components are used across multiple pages (catalog lookup, circulation shelving, etc.).
ShelfSection is the canonical entity. Map nodes must correspond to ShelfSection records in the database. Do not invent alternative data structures for shelf positioning. The mapX, mapY, width, and height fields on ShelfSection are the source of truth for node placement.
React Flow is the only canvas library. Do not introduce D3, Konva, Fabric.js, or raw Canvas API. All map rendering goes through @xyflow/react.
13.9 Handling Gaps
If this spec does not cover a situation you encounter, apply these rules in order:
Check if a similar pattern is already established elsewhere in the spec. Follow it.
Check the existing codebase for a precedent. Match the established pattern.
Choose the approach that is most consistent with the three-layer architecture (Section 5).
Choose the simpler of two reasonable approaches.
Leave a // SPEC QUESTION: comment explaining your choice.

